14.7.1.¶

We have $$\Delta u = \Delta v + \Delta w = f + 0 = f$$ in $\Omega$, and so it satisfies the first equation. Furthermore, $$u = v + w = v + (g-v) = g$$ on $\partial \Omega$, and so the second condition is also satisfied.

14.7.4¶

With a mesh width of $h=0.01$ and time step of $0.00006$ the method is unstable, but it is stable when $\Delta t=0.00005$. This lines up perfectly with the inequality $$\frac{\Delta t}{h^2}\le \frac12$$ which is theoretically when stability occurs.

Code follows:

In [104]:
t = 0
dt = 0.00005
n = 100
dx = 1/n
x = np.linspace(0, 1, n+1)
u = [(i*dx)*(1-i*dx) for i in range(n+1)]
plt.plot(x, u)
while abs(t-1) > dt/2:
    t += dt
    prev_u = u
    u = np.zeros(n+1)
    for i in range(1, n):
        u[i] = prev_u[i] + dt/dx**2 * (-2*prev_u[i] + prev_u[i+1] + prev_u[i-1])

plt.plot(x, u)
plt.show()
